text:
The cover athlete curse has been a well-known phenomenon for decades now. It’s most commonly associated with the NFL and its flagship game Madden, having strong claims originating back to 2002 and 2004 with the injury-plagued seasons of Dante Culpepper and Michael Vick. But does the curse go outside of football?
What about baseball?
Baseball has been in the United States longer than Colorado has been a state. But yet, America’s pastime does not escape video game superstition.
To analyze the effects that the cover athlete curse has on the MLB, it’s crucial to place the athletes on a common denominator that equally favors slap hitters and power hitters, catchers and shortstops, and the list goes on. In baseball, as simple as it gets, this statistic is Wins Above Replacement (WAR). This measures how many more wins an athlete contributes to a team compared to that of a replacement-level player.


Code
library(tidyverse)
library(ggrepel)
library(patchwork)
library(ggalt)
library(ggtext)
library(ggplot2)

logs &lt;- read_csv("mlb_hitter_value_2009_2024 (4).csv")
fixedlogs &lt;- logs |&gt;  mutate(Player=gsub("#", "", Player)) |&gt; 
  mutate(Player=gsub("\\*", "", Player))
coverathletes &lt;- fixedlogs |&gt; 
  filter(
    Player == "Joe Mauer" |
      Player == "Adrián González"  |
      Player == "Andrew McCutchen" |
      Player == "Miguel Cabrera" |
      Player == "Yasiel Puig" |
      Player == "Josh Donaldson" |
      Player == "Aaron Judge" |
      Player == "Bryce Harper" |
      Player == "Javier Báez" |
      Player == "Fernando Tatis Jr." |
      Player == "Shohei Ohtani" |
      Player == "Jazz Chisholm Jr." |
      Player == "Vladimir Guerrero Jr.") |&gt; 
    select(season, Player, Age, Team, WAR) |&gt; 
  filter(
    season != 2020
  )
Mauer &lt;- coverathletes |&gt; 
  filter(Player == "Joe Mauer") |&gt; 
  filter(season &gt; 2009) |&gt; 
  filter(season &lt; 2013)
EMauer &lt;- Mauer |&gt; 
  filter(season == 2011)
